79","1346–1445":"1346–1445","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1244–1314":"1244–1314","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","12 November 1314":"12. november 1314","1349":"1349","12 November 1348":"12. november 1348","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1346":"1346","1445":"1445","1379":"1379","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1244":"1244","1329":"1329","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Skotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland","Rousnot, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1290–1356":"1290–1356","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1330–1379":"1330–1379","1346–1445":"1346–1445","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1244–1314":"1244–1314","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","12 November 1314":"12 november 1314","1349":"1349","12 November 1348":"12 november 1348","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1346":"1346","1445":"1445","1379":"1379","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1244":"1244","1329":"1329","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Rousnot, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1290–1356":"1290–1356","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1330–1379":"1330–1379","1346–1445":"1346–1445","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1244–1314":"1244–1314","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","12 November 1314":"12 November 1314","1349":"1349","12 November 1348":"12 November 1348","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1346":"1346","1445":"1445","1379":"1379","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1244":"1244","1329":"1329","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rousnot, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Finley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: from the Gaelic personal name <i>Fionnlagh</i> (Old Irish <i>Findlaech</i>), from <i>fionn</i> ‘white, fair’ (see   Finn  ) + <i>laoch</i> ‘hero’, reinforced by an Old Norse name based on <i>finn</i> ‘Finn’ + <i>leikr</i> ‘fight’ or ‘hero’. The name is common in Ireland as well as Scotland.","English: habitational name from one or more lost, unidentified or altered placenames so named, such as Philleyholme, Dorset (recorded as <i>Finelegh</i> in 1280) derived from Old English <i>fīna</i> ‘wood-pecker’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Also a variant of <b>Findlow</b>, from Finlow Hill in Over Alderley, Cheshire (from Old English <i>fīn</i> ‘heap’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ meaning ‘heaped mound’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Finn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Aidan, Bridie, Brigid, Declan, Dierdra, Eoin, Keelin, Maeve, Niall, Seamus.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Finn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fionn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘white’ or ‘fair-haired’; it is often found Anglicized as   White  . This name is borne by several families in the west of Ireland.","English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Fin(n)</i> (Old Norse <i>Finnr</i>, <i>Fin</i>, originally ‘Finn’), used both as a byname and as a short form of various compound names with this first element."]},{"name":"Finlayson","meanings":["Scottish: from the Gaelic personal name <i>Fionnlagh</i> (see   Finley   1 and   Finlay  ) + <i>-son</i>. This is the Anglicized form of Scottish Gaelic <i>MacFhionnlaigh</i>."]},{"name":"Findlay","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Finley   1."]},{"name":"Finlay","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Finley   1."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Finley Royal Forester was born in 1290, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Archibald Finley, was 42 and his mother, Margaret Robertson, was 46. He married Isabell Dempster in 1329, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1356, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 66, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1290–1356":"1290–1356","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1330–1379":"1330–1379","1346–1445":"1346–1445","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1244–1314":"1244–1314","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","12 November 1314":"12. november 1314","1349":"1349","12 November 1348":"12. november 1348","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1346":"1346","1445":"1445","1379":"1379","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1244":"1244","1329":"1329","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rousnot, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–1356":"1290–1356","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1330–1379":"1330–1379","1346–1445":"1346–1445","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1244–1314":"1244–1314","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","12 November 1314":"12. marraskuuta 1314","1349":"1349","12 November 1348":"12. marraskuuta 1348","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1346":"1346","1445":"1445","1379":"1379","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1244":"1244","1329":"1329","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rousnot, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Skot